17 "§410.3. Purpose and nature of party primary elections
18 A. For general elections, major political parties shall make all nominations
19 of candidates for party primary office by direct primary elections held pursuant to
20 this Part. In party primary elections, each voter voting in such election may vote
21 only for a candidate who is affiliated with the same party as the voter. However, the
22 state central committee of a major political party may in its bylaws allow voters who
23 are not affiliated with a political party to participate in its party primary elections.
24 B.(1) Voters not affiliated with a political party may vote in a major party
25 primary if a party primary ballot is selected by the voter prior to casting his ballot,
26 but such a voter may vote only in one major party primary. If an unaffiliated voter
27 chooses to vote in the first party primary of one political party, the unaffiliated voter
28 shall not vote in the second party primary of another political party. The state central
29 committee of a major political party shall notify the Department of State at least one
30 hundred eighty days prior to the opening of qualifying for the first party primary that
31 its bylaws allow for participation by voters not affiliated with a political party. The
32 notification shall be considered valid when the state central committee submits to the
33 Department of State a letter, on the major political party's letterhead and signed by
34 the state central committee's chairman, and a copy of the major political party's
35 current bylaws.
36 (2) If the state central committee of a major political party prohibits an
37 unaffiliated voter from participating in its primary elections, the state central
38 committee of such party shall notify the Department of State at least one hundred
39 eighty days prior to the opening of qualifying for the first party primary that the state
40 central committee prohibits participation by voters not affiliated with a political
